From part 2, we know that the correct crs of this CHM raster file is EPSG:32613 and there should be no "no data value.

In [9]:
# Does lidar_chm GeoTIFF file has the correct crs and 'no data value'?
print(lidar_chm.rio.crs)
print(lidar_chm.rio.nodata)

EPSG:32613
None

It shows that the crs of lidar_chm is EPSG:32613, which match up the correct one. Also, "no data value" is none since the output of lidar_chm.rio.nodata is 'None'.

Explanation (Working Process):¶

The first step to achieve this part is of course import related packages such as earthpy, rioxarray, and numpy (In cell 13). Then, setting up the initial catalog. This is important because we need to set up Tdirectory to access and load raster files. According to this question, we need two raster files, one DTM, one DSM, from pre flood and post flood respectively. Here we adjust relative paths to those files and obtain CHM files by calculating "pre_flood_dsm" minus "pre_flood_dtm" and "post_flood_dsm" minus "post_flood_dtm" also respectively. From practices, we know that there are no data value in each DTM and DSM, we need to remove them by using function "squeeze", and we also need to check if they have the same crs, resolution(In cell 18). To double check if there is any no data value, plot histogram of each CHM files (In cell 19). Since we are looking for the difference between these two CHM files, we need to calculate post_chm minus pre_chm (In cell 22). Once we have thet CHM file of difference between pre flood and post flood, we're ready to working forward.\ To make a plot that present useful information, first thing we need to do is determining how do we plot the map. Draw a histogram plot of difference between pre flood and post flood to see which bins are data mostly located (In cell 23). Once confirmed, we're able to decide which bins are we going to use and draw our map. Here, data are mainly distributed between -10 and 10, and this determines that we need to draw a diverging map. and then plot it. This is the key step to reclassify raster data. It clearly shows that area present the value of 6 is not what we need, so we remove it.(In cell 24 and cell 25).Here, the value of 1 stands for "-np.inf", the value of 2 stands for "-5", the value of 3 stands for "-2", the value of 4 stands for "2", the value of 5 stands for "5", the value of 6 stands for "np.inf". Before we remove the data with value of 6, there are 6 classes. Once we removed it, there would be only 5 classes left. Now we reclassify the raster data and only select data we need. \ The final part is making this reclassified plot. The key manipulation here is set correct bins. We cannot use previous bins here cause we need a new bins that work with reclassfied data, and we need to let each bin include the integer value (mentioned above), so the first bin better start with 0 and end with 1.5. In this case, the value of 1 and value around it are included in this bin. Then, add title and legend. (In cell 26)
